# Methodology

## Research Design

This study adopted a comparative evaluation approach to analyse multiple Privacy-Preserving Data Publishing (PPDP) techniques using a unified assessment framework.

The methodology focused on balancing three key objectives:

* Privacy Protection
* Data Utility
* Computational Performance

A composite scoring model was developed to support decision-making and technique selection.

---

## Dataset Selection

The Adult Income Dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository was selected because it contains demographic and socio-economic information commonly used in privacy-preserving data publishing research.

After preprocessing, the dataset contained 30,162 records suitable for experimentation and machine learning evaluation.

---

## Data Preprocessing

The following preprocessing activities were conducted:

* Missing value handling
* Data cleaning
* Feature transformation
* Categorical encoding
* Dataset standardisation

---

## Privacy-Preserving Techniques

Three representative techniques were evaluated:

### k-Anonymity

Implemented using generalisation and quantile-based binning to reduce re-identification risk.

### Differential Privacy

Implemented using Laplace noise injection to provide mathematical privacy guarantees.

### Synthetic Data Generation

Implemented using bootstrap-based sampling techniques to generate privacy-preserving synthetic records.

---

## Machine Learning Evaluation

The utility of each privacy-preserved dataset was evaluated using machine learning models:

* Logistic Regression
* Decision Tree
* Random Forest
* XGBoost

Performance metrics were used to determine how well predictive capabilities were preserved after privacy transformation.

---

## Composite Scoring Framework

A weighted scoring model was developed:

Privacy Score = 40%

Utility Score = 40%

Computational Performance = 20%

The final composite score was calculated to provide a balanced evaluation of each privacy-preserving technique.

---

## Decision Support

The final ranking mechanism was designed to assist organisations and researchers in selecting the most suitable privacy-preserving technique based on overall performance.

